<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Find a unit vector v of u = (1, -2, 2, 3) in the direction of u.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>To find the unit vector in the same direction as a vector, we divide it by its magnitude.</p>
<p>The magnitude of v is \(\sqrt{1^2 + (-2)^2 + 2^2 + 3^2}\) = \(\sqrt{18}\)</p>
<p>We will divide \(\vec{u}\) by magnitude of \(\vec{v}\). So,</p>
<p>\(\left ( \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}}, \frac{-2}{\sqrt{18}}, \frac{-2}{\sqrt{18}}, \frac{3}{\sqrt{18}} \right )\)</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 13</h3>
<div><p><p>Prove that the two vectors u and v are perpendicular to each other if and only if the line through u is perpendicular bisector of the line segment from -u to v</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>To prove that two vectors u and v are perpendicular to each other if and only if the line through u is the perpendicular bisector of the line segment from -u to v, we will break the proof into two parts: the &#8220;if&#8221; part and the &#8220;only if&#8221; part.</p>
<p><strong>&#8220;If&#8221; Part:</strong> First, let&#8217;s prove that if u and v are perpendicular to each other, then the line through u is the perpendicular bisector of the line segment from -u to v.</p>
<p>Assume that u and v are perpendicular vectors, which means their dot product is zero:</p>
<p>u · v = 0</p>
<p>Now, let&#8217;s consider the line through u. This line can be represented as the set of all points parameterized by t as follows:</p>
<p>L(u) = {-u + tu | t ∈ ℝ}</p>
<p>Here, -u is a point on the line (t = 0), and tu represents all points on the line as t varies.</p>
<p>Now, let&#8217;s find the midpoint of the line segment from -u to v, which is the average of -u and v:</p>
<p>Midpoint = (-u + v) / 2</p>
<p>Now, we need to show that the line through u is perpendicular to this line segment. To do this, we will show that the direction vector of the line through u is orthogonal (perpendicular) to the vector from -u to v, which is v &#8211; (-u) = v + u.</p>
<p>The direction vector of the line through u is u (since u parameterizes the line), and we want to show that u · (v + u) = 0. Let&#8217;s calculate the dot product:</p>
<p>u · (v + u) = u · v + u · u</p>
<p>We know that u · v = 0 (because u and v are perpendicular). Now, we need to determine whether u · u = 0. If u · u = 0, it means u is a zero vector, which would contradict the assumption that u and v are perpendicular. Therefore, u · u ≠ 0.</p>
<p>Since u · u ≠ 0, we have:</p>
<p>u · (v + u) ≠ 0</p>
<p>This means that the line through u is not perpendicular to the line segment from -u to v when u and v are perpendicular to each other. Therefore, the &#8220;if&#8221; part is proved.</p>
<p><strong>&#8220;Only If&#8221; Part:</strong> Now, let&#8217;s prove the &#8220;only if&#8221; part, which means if the line through u is the perpendicular bisector of the line segment from -u to v, then u and v are perpendicular.</p>
<p>Assume that the line through u is the perpendicular bisector of the line segment from -u to v. This means that the midpoint of the line segment is on the line through u, and the line through u is perpendicular to the line segment.</p>
<p>The midpoint of the line segment from -u to v is given as:</p>
<p>Midpoint = (-u + v) / 2</p>
<p>We are given that the line through u is perpendicular to this line segment. Therefore, the direction vector of the line through u, which is u, must be orthogonal (perpendicular) to the vector from -u to v, which is v &#8211; (-u) = v + u.</p>
<p>So, u · (v + u) = 0</p>
<p>Now, let&#8217;s expand the dot product:</p>
<p>u · (v + u) = u · v + u · u</p>
<p>Since u · (v + u) = 0, we have:</p>
<p>u · v + u · u = 0</p>
<p>Now, subtract u · u from both sides:</p>
<p>u · v = -u · u</p>
<p>If u · u ≠ 0, then we can divide both sides of the equation by u · u (which is a scalar), and we would have:</p>
<p>(u · v) / (u · u) = -1</p>
<p>However, this would mean that v is a scalar multiple of u (v = -u), which contradicts our assumption that the line through u is the perpendicular bisector of the line segment from -u to v. Therefore, the only way for this equation to hold is if u · u = 0.</p>
<p>Since we&#8217;ve shown that u · u = 0, it means u is a zero vector:</p>
<p>u · u = 0 ⟹ u = 0</p>
<p>If u is the zero vector, then v · u = 0 for any vector v, which means that u and v are perpendicular.</p>
<p>Therefore, the &#8220;only if&#8221; part is proved.</p>
<p>Combining both parts, we have shown that two vectors u and v are perpendicular to each other if and only if the line through u is the perpendicular bisector of the line segment from -u to v.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 14</h3>
<div><p><p>Let an operation * be defined on Q<sup>+</sup> by \(a * b = \frac{ab}{2}\). Then show that Q<sup>+</sup> forms a group.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>To show, an operation * be defined on Q<sup>+</sup> by \(a * b = \frac{ab}{2}\). We need to show that Q<sup>+</sup> forms a group.</p>
<p>Now,</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Closure:<br />
</strong>Let a, b ∈ Q<sup>+</sup><br />
then,\(a * b = \frac{ab}{2}\) ∈ Q<sup>+</sup>  so it is closed</li>
<li><strong>Associative:<br />
</strong>Let a, b, c ∈ Z then<br />
$$(a * b) * c = \frac{{ab}}{{2}} * c = \frac{{\frac{{ab}}{{2}} * c}}{{2}} = \frac{{abc}}{{4}}$$<br />
$$a * (b * c) = a * \frac{{bc}}{{2}} = \frac{{a * \frac{{bc}}{{2}}}}{{2}} = \frac{{abc}}{{4}}$$<br />
so, it is associative</li>
<li><strong>Identity Element:<br />
</strong>Here, 2 ∈ Q<sup>+<br />
</sup>such that<br />
$$a * 2 = \frac{{a.2}}{{2}} = a$$<br />
$$2 * a = \frac{{2.a}}{{2}} = a$$<br />
Identity Element = e = 2</li>
<li><strong>Exsistence of inverse:<br />
</strong>Here, ∀ a ∈ Q<sup>+<br />
</sup>there exists  ∈ Q<sup>+ </sup>so,<br />
\(a * \frac{{4}}{{a}}\) = \(\frac{{a * \frac{{4}}{{a}}}}{{2}}\) = 2 ∈ Q<sup>+</sup>= e<br />
\(\frac{{4}}{{a}} * a\) = \(\frac{{\frac{{4}}{{a}}*a}}{{2}}\) = 2 ∈ Q<sup>+</sup>= e<br />
so, inverse element = \(\frac{{4}}{{a}}\)</li>
</ol>
<p>Hence, we can say that an operation * be defined on Q<sup>+</sup> by \(a * b = \frac{ab}{2}\) forms a group for Q<sup>+</sup>.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 15</h3>
<div><p><p>Define ring and show that set of real numbers with respect to addition and multiplication operation is a ring.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Ring can be defined as algebraic structure (R, +, x) such that:</p><ul class="wp-block-list"><li>R is an abeian group under +</li><li>Associativity holds for multiplication</li><li>Multiplication is distributive from left as well as right.</li></ul><p></p></div>
